,["up","","Buzz","Everett Bogue","\u003cb\u003eWhat is untethering?\u003c/b\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eUntethering is asking the question ‘why’ of everything in my life. If I can’t figure out a good reason for it exist, I cut the tether.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eA tether is the tie that binds me to something I’m clinging to. I can be tethered to things, ideas, places, people, structures, cults, cultures, ways of being in the world, and more.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eI almost always choose the tether, it often doesn’t choose me. I’m tethered to my Macbook Air, I choose this. I’m tethered to the gravity of this planet, I don’t choose this. While it may seem I can’t live without my computer, and I can’t escape the pull of gravity – there are people who do both in the world, so this isn’t true at all.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003ePadding is what I do when I’m trying to avoid the fact that when I ask ‘why’ I can’t find a good reason. Padding is avoiding the fact that my needs are no longer satisfied. Instead of saying ‘wow, I need more freedom and autonomy’ I instead drink another beer. Many things which may seem to be useful are, in reality, padding. Many of the things sold in television commercials are padding.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eGripping is what I do right before I let go. It’s a passing moment where I convince myself I need something, when I really don’t. For the first two years of being location independent, I traveled with a giant metal bike lock in the bottom of my bag. No bike, just a bike lock. I gripped this because I felt it gave me security. In reality, it weighed me down.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eAll change and growth in my life comes from first untethering.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eI need to let go of something, before I can start something new.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eUntethering is it leads to uncertainty. When I cut a tether, I no longer have the anchor of doing something unnecessary with my life. I feel groundless. I don’t know what I’m going to do next with my life. Sometimes this leads to feeling scared, because I’m not sure what’s going to come next.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eHowever, what comes next almost always grows me. It’s almost always worth it.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eThis is why I untether.",1332391603130,"https://web.archive.org/web/20120322202814/http://www.google.com/favicon.ico",[]
,"z12ydz2qau3czr5dd23dslbqpvumyjjhr04","","s:updates:esshare",[]
,[]
,"",,[]
,"116298207273891385223",[]
,"//web.archive.org/web/20120322202814/https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-DTGZ0HgahRo/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAB48/rnwhNOjnFmE/photo.jpg",,"What is untethering?\n\nUntethering is asking the question ‘why’ of everything in my life. If I can’t figure out a good reason for it exist, I cut the tether.\n\nA tether is the tie that binds me to something I’m clinging to. I can be tethered to things, ideas, places, people, structures, cults, cultures, ways of being in the world, and more.\n\nI almost always choose the tether, it often doesn’t choose me. I’m tethered to my Macbook Air, I choose this. I’m tethered to the gravity of this planet, I don’t choose this. While it may seem I can’t live without my computer, and I can’t escape the pull of gravity – there are people who do both in the world, so this isn’t true at all.\n\nPadding is what I do when I’m trying to avoid the fact that when I ask ‘why’ I can’t find a good reason. Padding is avoiding the fact that my needs are no longer satisfied. Instead of saying ‘wow, I need more freedom and autonomy’ I instead drink another beer. Many things which may seem to be useful are, in reality, padding. Many of the things sold in television commercials are padding.\n\nGripping is what I do right before I let go. It’s a passing moment where I convince myself I need something, when I really don’t. For the first two years of being location independent, I traveled with a giant metal bike lock in the bottom of my bag. No bike, just a bike lock. I gripped this because I felt it gave me security. In reality, it weighed me down.\n\nAll change and growth in my life comes from first untethering.\n\nI need to let go of something, before I can start something new.\n\nUntethering is it leads to uncertainty. When I cut a tether, I no longer have the anchor of doing something unnecessary with my life. I feel groundless. I don’t know what I’m going to do next with my life. Sometimes this leads to feeling scared, because I’m not sure what’s going to come next.\n\nHowever, what comes next almost always grows me. It’s almost always worth it.\n\nThis is why I untether.","116298207273891385223/posts/7tR92RS7gxB",0,0.0,"./116298207273891385223",[["Chris French","100587537217705462238",1,1,,"./100587537217705462238"]
,["Muhammed Yildirim","116721904145892189404",1,1,,"./116721904145892189404"]
