,["up","","Buzz","Everett Bogue","\u003cb\u003eThe future of the evolving book\u003c/b\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eFor the last six months I’ve lived in flexible housing situations – Airbnb, hotels in Mexico, etc. I do this was because I want greater autonomy in my life. I could be tied down with a 6-month or 1-year lease. But do I want to?\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eLiving in a flexible living situation gives me greater freedom. If I want to leave at the end of the month, I can.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eWhen I reworked \u003ci\u003eMinimalist Business\u003c/i\u003e, I put a lot of thought into what format to release the book in. The original edition was a PDF, designed in Indesign. This new version is compiled using Kindle’s .mobi format.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eThe reason I choose the .mobi format is this: I want to experiment with a flexible format. You, the reader, get to choose how the book is displayed. I, the writer, get to easily compile new versions of the book using Scrivener. This way, I can easily evolve the content of the book as my experience of the world changes. The book will expand and contract based on what I feel is the most beneficial way to present the book to you right now.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eUsing a flexible book format gives me greater freedom. If I want to change a part of the book I can. If I find a mistake, I can fix it in the next version.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eThe challenge with this decision is we’ve been thinking of the book as solid since the Gutenberg press was invented. We\u0026#39;re used to all of the book production happening before the book ends up in our hands. We\u0026#39;re used to books being two years out of date by the time we read them. We’re all used to bricked books.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eNow, we’re amidst the next evolution of the book. I’m beginning to see the book as a flexible object, which lives and grows with the information inside it.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eReading/writing a flexible book is a new kind of challenge for me and for you.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eThere are many questions in my mind right now about the evolving book… and how I will overcome them will be told in time.",1332186538184,"https://web.archive.org/web/20120322202814/http://www.google.com/favicon.ico",[]
,"z13bybgrkyrsyn34w04chb24yurjeftxxqw0k","","s:updates:esshare",[]
,[]
,"",,[]
,"116298207273891385223",[]
,"//web.archive.org/web/20120322202814/https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-DTGZ0HgahRo/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAB48/rnwhNOjnFmE/photo.jpg",,"The future of the evolving book\n\nFor the last six months I’ve lived in flexible housing situations – Airbnb, hotels in Mexico, etc. I do this was because I want greater autonomy in my life. I could be tied down with a 6-month or 1-year lease. But do I want to?\n\nLiving in a flexible living situation gives me greater freedom. If I want to leave at the end of the month, I can.\n\nWhen I reworked Minimalist Business, I put a lot of thought into what format to release the book in. The original edition was a PDF, designed in Indesign. This new version is compiled using Kindle’s .mobi format.\n\nThe reason I choose the .mobi format is this: I want to experiment with a flexible format. You, the reader, get to choose how the book is displayed. I, the writer, get to easily compile new versions of the book using Scrivener. This way, I can easily evolve the content of the book as my experience of the world changes. The book will expand and contract based on what I feel is the most beneficial way to present the book to you right now.\n\nUsing a flexible book format gives me greater freedom. If I want to change a part of the book I can. If I find a mistake, I can fix it in the next version.\n\nThe challenge with this decision is we’ve been thinking of the book as solid since the Gutenberg press was invented. We're used to all of the book production happening before the book ends up in our hands. We're used to books being two years out of date by the time we read them. We’re all used to bricked books.\n\nNow, we’re amidst the next evolution of the book. I’m beginning to see the book as a flexible object, which lives and grows with the information inside it.\n\nReading/writing a flexible book is a new kind of challenge for me and for you.\n\nThere are many questions in my mind right now about the evolving book… and how I will overcome them will be told in time.","116298207273891385223/posts/T7NKdCtyhwc",0,0.0,"./116298207273891385223",[]
,,,"",0,1332186538184053,1,1,"\u003cb\u003eThe future of the evolving book\u003c/b\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eFor the last six months I’ve lived in flexible housing situations – Airbnb, hotels in Mexico, etc. I do this was because I want greater autonomy in my life. I could be tied down with a 6-month or 1-year lease. But do I want to?\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eLiving in a flexible living situation gives me greater freedom. If I want to leave at the end of the month, I can.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eWhen I reworked \u003ci\u003eMinimalist Business...\u003c/i\u003e",0,0,"0",0,1332186538184,,,0,,,,0,,,,[]
